.TH "Touch.screenX" "JS" "July 25, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Touch.screenX \- Touch: screenX property
.SH SYNOPSIS
Returns the X coordinate of the touch point relative to the screen, not
including any scroll offset.
.SH VALUE
A number.
.SH EXAMPLES
This example illustrates how to access the \f[CR]Touch\f[R] object\[cq]s
\f[CR]Touch.screenX\f[R] and \f[CR]Touch.screenY\f[R] properties.
The \f[CR]Touch.screenX\f[R] property is the horizontal (x) coordinate
of a touch point relative to the screen in CSS pixels.
The \f[CR]Touch.screenY\f[R] property is the vertical coordinate of a
touch point relative to the screen in CSS pixels.
.PP
In following simple code snippet, we assume the user initiates multiple
touch contacts on an element with an id of \f[CR]source\f[R] and then
releases contacts with the surface.
When the \f[CR]touchstart\f[R] event handler is invoked, each touch
point\[cq]s \f[CR]Touch.screenX\f[R] and \f[CR]Touch.screenY\f[R]
coordinates are accessed.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Register a touchstart listeners for the \[aq]source\[aq] element\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] src = document.getElementById(\[dq]source\[dq]);

src.addEventListener(
  \[dq]touchstart\[dq],
  (e) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    \f[I]// Iterate through the touch points and log each screenX/Y coordinate.\f[R]
    \f[I]// The unit of each coordinate is CSS pixels.\f[R]
    \f[B]for\f[R] (\f[B]let\f[R] i = 0; i < e.touches.length; i++) {
      console.log(\[ga]touchpoint[${i}].screenX = ${e.touches[i].screenX}\[ga]);
      console.log(\[ga]touchpoint[${i}].screenY = ${e.touches[i].screenY}\[ga]);
    }
  },
  \f[B]false\f[R],
);
.EE
